The paper focuses on evaluating human motion prediction models in the context of human-robot collaboration, which falls under the robotics (cs.RO) sub-category. The use of neural networks for parameterization suggests a focus on artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG). The evaluation of closed-loop performance and safety considerations suggest a focus on human-computer interaction (cs.HC). Finally, the use of computer vision techniques for motion tracking may also suggest a focus on computer vision (cs.CV).
